Melissa Barerra gets to go absolutely unhinged and stab the shit out of crazy white folks and all of the POC make it to the end? Hot damn. I’m even more sad this continuity won’t continue due to the production company being Zionist bootlickers!
I feel like a lot of the people pearl-clutching over Saltburn would actually combust at seeing this movie.
Firing Melissa Barerra from future movies in the franchise because she’s pro-Palestine is one of the most boneheaded moves ever made because she ate this shit up.

A nice, fun lil' movie. I can imagine this really hit hard for someone who has fond memories of the original films but the nostalgia feels a bit dulled as someone who has only seen the much-derided 2016 reboot.

Story time. I've made watching this movie on New Year's Eve anytime I'm spending it away from friends a semi-regular/occasional tradition. It started back in 2015. I was supposed to go hang out with some friends from high school but those plans didn't pan out as my grandfather had died a few days before after getting unexpectedly and rapidly shortly after Christmas. The first part of his service was happening on New Year's Day and my mom wasn't too keen…
I've never seen a movie both praise God and demand men find the clit in musical form before. Or at all.
Started out hating Paul Giamatti’s character and left hoping that grumpy son of a bitch gets all the things he wants in the world.

DC really never got a good handle on sequels to their movies besides The Suicide Squad, did they? And even that was a sequel/reboot!The first Aquaman is one of my favorite DC movies, but this one just doesn't quite hit the same bar. It feels like James Wan kinda forgot how hard he went with the visuals and fight scenes in the first and just made a sequel that isn't quite as good. I will say though, Patrick Wilson…
I refuse to listen to anyone that doesn’t think this shit goes hard as fuck.
The white man's hubris leads to his demise once again.

Cinematography and direction were pretty fucking great. Didn't feel low-rent like some Netflix movies do and had some honestly inspired choices in the visuals.That being said, I don't know who this is for? I feel like the narrative wasn't as tight and focused as the average horror/thriller fan would want. Takes too long for things to ramp up so I don't think they'd like it.It also doesn't really push hard on the social commentary angle which kinda annoyed…
